{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c4f7bf44-eb13-44d1-bf63-3df79ad52fc9","content":"There's no repo-specific documentation here on this topic, but I can answer from general .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   This tells the OS to write core files when a process crashes.\n\n2. **Set the core dump location** (macOS stores them in `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   Look for a file like `core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **If `/cores/` is empty**, ensure SIP isn't blocking core dumps:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze the dump with `lldb`** (ships with Xcode):\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Then use `bt` (backtrace), `thread list`, `frame variable`, etc.\n\n5. **For managed stack traces**, load the SOS/dotnet debugging plugin in lldb:\n   ```bash\n   (lldb) plugin load /path/to/libsosplugin.dylib\n   ```\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT binaries include native symbols, so `lldb` backtraces are often readable without SOS. If your app was built with `<StripSymbols>false</StripSymbols>`, you'll get full symbol names in the trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a80b041a-a6bb-4107-a22e-cd548b6d1905","outputTokens":358,"requestId":"C3CA:1ABF8A:1DDB86C:2177266:6A07C2B8"},"id":"4efefda5-8cfa-44b8-af8d-28860aa3dcaf","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:05:05.761Z","parentId":"6e6c439d-8397-4b4e-a273-3c64583fc7be"}
